                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/3808: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-05-01T14:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 1, 1922—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>106. Continental and Commercial Bank states that it has received a telegram from
                    the Ministry of Finance stating that “coupons and commission May last $165,825.
                    will be paid when we receive salt surplus in June and July.” Bank requests that
                    the Legation bring this matter to the attention of the Chinese Government
                    shortly before the salt releases are made so that the commitment will not be
                    overlooked.</p>
                <p>You may also remind Chinese Government that on May 1, 1922, four semi-annual
                    interest payments were due in addition to the principal of the loan and other
                    expenses as provided for in the contract.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
